nib.text:
Crowds gathered outside the Brooklyn Center Police Department for the fifth consecutive night Thursday as demonstrators called for justice in the shooting of Daunte Wright.

Activists projected a “Justice 4 Daunte” sign across the street from police headquarters which remained fenced off with multiple law enforcement nearby.

After an emergency City Council meeting Thursday night, Brooklyn Center Mayor Mike Elliott announced a curfew would be in effect at 10 p.m. Thursday and last until 6 a.m Friday.

nib.text:
April 15 is the day of Minnesota’s statewide tornado drill. Hennepin County and Ramsey County will participate by sounding outdoor warning sirens twice, once at 1:45 p.m. for those in schools or businesses and a second time at 6:45 p.m. for families.

The drills are part of Minnesota Severe Weather Awareness Week. In Hennepin County, nearly two-thirds of federally declared disasters have been due to tornadoes and other severe weather since 1960. This week serves as a reminder to create, update, and practice household and workplace emergency plans.

Sirens alert people who are outdoors of severe weather warnings and other dangerous situations that threaten their safety. Those who are indoors may not hear the sirens and instead should rely on another means to get warnings, such as a NOAA weather radio and local television or radio stations.
